A simple customizable bracelet. The band has a circular cross section, flattened on the sides to facilitate easy printing. You control the inner (wrist) diameter, the band diameter, and the number of notches. Less stretchy than my ruffled bracelet because the curved inner and outer surfaces yield no easily-bent straight corners, but still quite flexible. The output is a solid model intended to be printed with no infill and no top or bottom layers. (Makerware users may find this how-to helpful.) Gratuitous cat video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0YzrRmXbmnM

Sample bracelet printed in sky blue Colorfabb PHA/PLA with my Printrbot Simple at 195 degrees C. 0.3 mm layer height.  
I recommend printing with no raft or brim so that both sides of the bracelet are clean and clear of burrs or extra material. So, make sure your bed is level and you have good adhesion.

title: Dual E3D hot end upgrade for Mankati Fullscale XT

description.text: OBSOLETE version. EDIT: please use this instead http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:295495 Just installed this double E3D hotend on my Fullscale XT. Double printing pleasure. It is like a puzzle to mount this, if there is no hurry, please wait for the redesigned mount that fixes more easily directly to the crossbars.

Flip the parts to suit your printing options. You have 3 parts:
  • fan shroud for the double 30mm fans that come with the E3D's
  • baseplate where the 2 E3D's get fixed
  • fixer plate, that holds the 2 hotends together in the right position
    • Assemble hotend per manufacturers directions.
    Slide the hotends in the baseplate, fix them with the fixing plate and screw the plates to the effector with 4 M3 screws.
    I would suggest changing the Mankati PTFE Bowden tube for a better one and also keeping it as short as possible. Fix the 2 fans with M3 screws directly into the plastic housing. Slide the fan shroud on the hotend. For the fans, use the right (second) fan cable, it is always powered, as it should be. Don't forget to print and install the longer Z end-stop holder, as it is now, this design looses about 1cm in Z height. Click for firmware using the new thermistors
    Follow the link and at the bottom of the page click "Build it" and download the whole zip file, extract .hex file and flash from Cura.
    Finally, you will have true temperature shown (original Mankati firmware was showing 30C too much to protect the lousy hotends). Never shut down the printer before the hotend cools down!

title: Open Beam OB1.4 profile reduction for belt with 20T

description.text:
As I wanted to keep a good precision for printing, I decided to keep my 20T pulley but didn't fit with the 15*15 open beam profile. Just have to cut the low profile in front of OB1.4.
Remove 25mm profile and cut it into 2 parts of 182.5mm, put this printed part in the middle and you've now got the right to put a little pulley! ;)
Be carefull to turn the piece to put the open side up to print ;)
Pictures to come Look at this OB 1.4 add-ons collection:

This one has negative holes where the pins are. they go all the way through.
4mm version is friendly to 3mm fillament, it goes in without complaint. (first)
3mm version probably fits mounting screws properly, or at least well enough to hold. (second)
pictured is 4mm with 3mm filament in it, intended for modeling, and i'm not going to use screws.
The center is still a bit large, I will add a replaceable insert for the motor so the attached gear rotates right, in the mean time, if you use a long strip, the bend of the filament alone will hold it in place.
I'm loving the concentric fill, even if your renticular won't close the gaps at the perimiters, concentric follows the shape and solves the outer shell problem.

title: Reasonably universal bowden swap kit
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
As I find more pieces I'll add them to the collection... marked "WIP" because of that.  The current files won't change unless somebody has recommendations.  
I have created adapters to change the standard 50mm-spaced extruders (all Prusa2 carriages and Wades-compatible extruders, including Greg's Accessible) into a Bowden setup.  This will allow you to move the heavy extruder motor off the X carriage and mount it rigidly to your frame instead.  
Currently sized to fit Arcol and Budaschnozzle hotends, Arcol should work on MakerGear and JHead as well.
